22 November 1404":"22 November 1404","1363":"1363","1330":"1330","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1404":"1404","1346":"1346","1434":"1434","1442":"1442","1420":"1420","1386":"1386","about 1385":"about 1385","Sonning, Berkshire, England":"Sonning, Berkshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Woodlands, Dorset, England":"Woodlands, Dorset, England","Buckingham, Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckingham, Buckinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Frome","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places so called, such as Frome (Somerset), Frome Saint Quintin, Frome Vauchurch, Frome Whitfield in Stinsford, the lost <i>Frome Billet</i> in West Stafford (all Dorset), Bishops Frome, Canon Frome, Castle Frome, and Prior's Frome and Larport (formerly <i>Frome</i>) both in Mordiford (all Herefordshire). Or a topographic name from the rivers on which these places are located, or simply a name for someone living beside a river of this name, which is probably cognate with Welsh <i>ffraw</i> ‘fair, fine, brisk’. Compare   Frampton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Frampton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places so called, of which there are several in Gloucestershire, one in Dorset and one in Lincolnshire. Most take the name from the Frome river in south Gloucestershire (which is probably from a British word meaning ‘fair, brisk’) + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. One near Tewkesbury was originally named in Old English as <i>Frēolingtūn</i> ‘settlement associated with <i>Frēola</i>’, a short form of any of various compound personal names with the first element <i>frēo</i> ‘free’. Frampton in Lincolnshire probably gets its name from an Old English byname <i>Frameca</i> (a derivative of <i>fram</i> ‘valiant’) + <i>tūn</i>."]},{"name":"Froom","meanings":["English: variant of   Frome  .","German: from a short form of a personal name composed with Middle High German <i>vrom</i>, <i>vrum</i> ‘valiant, steadfast’ (see   Frommelt  )."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":19,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Frome was born in 1363, in Buckinghamshire, England, his father, William Frome, was 34 and his mother, Elizabeth de Braose, was 17. He married Margaret de Tregos in 1382, in Buckingham, Buckinghamshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died on 22 November 1404, in his hometown, at the age of 41, and was buried in Sonning, Berkshire, England."},"et":{"1363–22 November 1404":"1363–22. november 1404","1363–1404":"1363–1404","1360–1420":"1360–1420","1385–1442":"1385–1442","1386–1434":"1386–1434","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1346–Female":"1346–Surnud","22 November 1404":"22. november 1404","1363":"1363","1330":"1330","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1404":"1404","1346":"1346","1434":"1434","1442":"1442","1420":"1420","1386":"1386","about 1385":"umbes 1385","Sonning, Berkshire, England":"Sonning, Berkshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Woodlands, Dorset, England":"Woodlands, Dorset, England","Buckingham, Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckingham, Buckinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"1363–22 November 1404":"1363–22. marraskuuta 1404","1363–1404":"1363–1404","1360–1420":"1360–1420","1385–1442":"1385–1442","1386–1434":"1386–1434","1330–Male":"1330–K